{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01CvzzM4ru9pUYpGrKHLNhuo", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Here's how to use `KubeletConfig` to customize kubelet settings for worker nodes:\n\n## Basic Structure\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: KubeletConfig\nmetadata:\n  name: worker-kubelet-custom\nspec:\n  machineConfigPoolSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      pools.operator.machineconfiguration.openshift.io/worker: \"\"\n  kubeletConfig:\n    maxPods: 500\n    podPidsLimit: 8192\n```\n\nApply it with:\n```bash\noc apply -f worker-kubelet-custom.yaml\n```\n\n## How it Works\n\n1. **`machineConfigPoolSelector`** \u2014 targets a MachineConfigPool by label. The built-in label `pools.operator.machineconfiguration.openshift.io/worker: \"\"` automatically matches the `worker` pool (OCP 4.6+).\n\n2. **`kubeletConfig`** \u2014 accepts any fields from the upstream Kubernetes [`KubeletConfiguration`](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/config-api/kubelet-config.v1beta1/) (`kubelet.config.k8s.io/v1beta1`). The MCO merges your settings on top of the defaults.\n\n**Defaults** (from `templates/worker/01-worker-kubelet/_base/files/kubelet.yaml`):\n- `maxPods: 250`\n- `podPidsLimit: 4096`\n\n## Workflow After Apply\n\nMCO will:\n1. Generate a new `MachineConfig` from the `KubeletConfig`\n2. Apply it to all nodes in the `worker` pool via a rolling reboot\n\nWatch the rollout:\n```bash\noc get machineconfigpool worker -w\n```\n\n## Custom Pool (Optional)\n\nIf you want to target only a subset of workers, use a custom label:\n\n```yaml\n# Label the MachineConfigPool first:\noc label machineconfigpool worker custom-kubelet=tuned\n\n# Then reference it in KubeletConfig:\nspec:\n  machineConfigPoolSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      custom-kubelet: tuned\n```\n\n## Multiple KubeletConfigs\n\nYou can have multiple `KubeletConfig` objects targeting the same pool \u2014 MCO merges them. Later-created configs take precedence on conflicting keys.\n\n**Key files for reference:**\n- `docs/KubeletConfigDesign.md` \u2014 full design doc with workflow details\n- `examples/kubeletconfig.crd.yaml` \u2014 minimal canonical example\n- `test/extended-priv/testdata/files/change-maxpods-kubelet-config.yaml` \u2014 maxPods test template"}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 3, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 3199, "cache_read_input_tokens": 33848, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 3199, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 7}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c2fd8390-c847-413c-9495-3acc22b6bd40", "uuid": "d18ba682-cfac-4785-b0c7-91c2e07f8932", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcJyoSMpQUsTtnnviwQqu", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:07:11.737Z"}
{"type": "result", "subtype": "success", "is_error": false, "api_error_status": null, "duration_ms": 99471, "duration_api_ms": 100196, "ttft_ms": 2172, "ttft_stream_ms": 1346, "time_to_request_ms": 20, "num_turns": 2, "result": "Here's how to use `KubeletConfig` to customize kubelet settings for worker nodes:\n\n## Basic Structure\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: KubeletConfig\nmetadata:\n  name: worker-kubelet-custom\nspec:\n  machineConfigPoolSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      pools.operator.machineconfiguration.openshift.io/worker: \"\"\n  kubeletConfig:\n    maxPods: 500\n    podPidsLimit: 8192\n```\n\nApply it with:\n```bash\noc apply -f worker-kubelet-custom.yaml\n```\n\n## How it Works\n\n1. **`machineConfigPoolSelector`** \u2014 targets a MachineConfigPool by label. The built-in label `pools.operator.machineconfiguration.openshift.io/worker: \"\"` automatically matches the `worker` pool (OCP 4.6+).\n\n2. **`kubeletConfig`** \u2014 accepts any fields from the upstream Kubernetes [`KubeletConfiguration`](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/config-api/kubelet-config.v1beta1/) (`kubelet.config.k8s.io/v1beta1`). The MCO merges your settings on top of the defaults.\n\n**Defaults** (from `templates/worker/01-worker-kubelet/_base/files/kubelet.yaml`):\n- `maxPods: 250`\n- `podPidsLimit: 4096`\n\n## Workflow After Apply\n\nMCO will:\n1. Generate a new `MachineConfig` from the `KubeletConfig`\n2. Apply it to all nodes in the `worker` pool via a rolling reboot\n\nWatch the rollout:\n```bash\noc get machineconfigpool worker -w\n```\n\n## Custom Pool (Optional)\n\nIf you want to target only a subset of workers, use a custom label:\n\n```yaml\n# Label the MachineConfigPool first:\noc label machineconfigpool worker custom-kubelet=tuned\n\n# Then reference it in KubeletConfig:\nspec:\n  machineConfigPoolSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      custom-kubelet: tuned\n```\n\n## Multiple KubeletConfigs\n\nYou can have multiple `KubeletConfig` objects targeting the same pool \u2014 MCO merges them. Later-created configs take precedence on conflicting keys.\n\n**Key files for reference:**\n- `docs/KubeletConfigDesign.md` \u2014 full design doc with workflow details\n- `examples/kubeletconfig.crd.yaml` \u2014 minimal canonical example\n- `test/extended-priv/testdata/files/change-maxpods-kubelet-config.yaml` \u2014 maxPods test template", "stop_reason": "end_turn", "session_id": "c2fd8390-c847-413c-9495-3acc22b6bd40", "total_cost_usd": 0.32834955000000005, "usage": {"input_tokens": 6, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 5998, "cache_read_input_tokens": 64897, "output_tokens": 986, "server_tool_use": {"web_search_requests": 0, "web_fetch_requests": 0}, "service_tier": "standard", "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0, "ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 5998}, "inference_geo": "", "iterations": [], "speed": "standard"}, "modelUsage": {"claude-sonnet-4-6": {"inputTokens": 402, "outputTokens": 6859, "cacheReadInputTokens": 319666, "cacheCreationInputTokens": 34229, "webSearchRequests": 0, "costUSD": 0.32834955000000005, "contextWindow": 200000, "maxOutputTokens": 32000}}, "permission_denials": [], "terminal_reason": "completed", "fast_mode_state": "off", "uuid": "331fc640-087a-4c21-b751-71cace615e3d", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:07:11.751Z"}